In the last sessions, you have learned quite a bit about handling data in R using packages from the tidyverse. However, the overarching goal of all this data wrangling always is to bring the data into the right shape for performing analyses which provide you with insights. Here, I focus on network analysis. There exist various possibilities of how to store network data. Most related to the tidy principles is using node- and edgelists.

Data on the nodes is stored in a tibble with at least one column containing the name of the node (or an id or something similar). Additional columns can be used to depict some kind of attributes of the node. They should be either factors or integers.

The edgelist then has at least to columns: from and to. The names in from and to must be the same is in the nodelist. Further columns can be used to stpre the weight of the connection and/or the type of connection.

abortion_nodes <- read_csv("data/abortion-bills/nodelist_abortion_bills.csv",
                           col_types = cols(
                             id = col_character(), # node names need to be characters
                             female = col_double(),
                             democrat = col_double()
))

For network analysis in R, igraph is one of the best reknown and versatile packages. However, it is not related to the tidyverse and might therefore be quite unintuitive for you to use. tidygraph fixes this problem. It basically brings together the best of both worlds: it builds upon igraph, and in fact, you can use all the functions from igraph, but still enables you to manipulate your data using classic dplyr code.

Getting started with tidygraph

Creating a tbl_graph object

tbl_graph objects are basically a subclass of igraph objects. This means that you can also apply igraph functions to them. However, most of the times you will not have to do this.

When analyzing networks in R with tidygraph, the first step always is to create a tbl_graph object. There is a couple of formats that can be transformed to a tbl_graph. I will exemplify the two most important kinds of representations: the sort of tidy one, with edge- and nodelists, and the one using an adjacency matrix.

The function for creating a tbl_graph is tbl_graph(). The nodelist needs to be provided with the nodes = argument, the edgelist with edges =. Another thing you need to provide is whether the network is directed and weighted.

library(tidygraph)
## 
## Attaching package: 'tidygraph'
## The following object is masked from 'package:igraph':
## 
##     groups
## The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter
graph <- tbl_graph(nodes = abortion_nodes, edges = abortion_edges, directed = FALSE)

For working with matrices, you can just use igraphs function and then transform the igraph object into a tbl_graph object.

matrix <- igraph::as_adjacency_matrix(graph)

However, for now, I will just create a toy example to work with. It is an Erds-Renyi graph. The function takes two arguments: the number of nodes and the probability that an edge exists between two of them (hence, the density). Then, a graph is drawn from all possible graphs which have those specifications.

# toy example
toy_example <- play_erdos_renyi(20, 0.5)

Working with tidygraph

activate()

A tbl_graph object basically is two tibbles, the nodelist and the edgelist.

toy_example
## # A tbl_graph: 20 nodes and 183 edges
## #
## # A directed simple graph with 1 component
## #
## # Node Data: 20 x 0 (active)
## #
## # Edge Data: 183 x 2
##    from    to
##   <int> <int>
## 1     2     1
## 2     3     1
## 3     5     1
## #  with 180 more rows

In the toy example, there is no node names because there are also numbers between 1 and 20. However, we can give them some attributes. The handy thing about tidygraph is that it works using dplyr syntax. To access the nodelist, you can activate() it. I will just add an id and a binary variable indicating whether the node is female or not. This can be achieved using mutate().

# activate()
toy_example_node_attr <- toy_example %>% 
  activate(nodes) %>% 
  mutate(name = 1:20,
         female = sample(0:1, 20, replace = TRUE, prob = c(0.9, 0.1)))

You can also export the nodelist just by using as_tibble().

toy_example_node_attr %>% 
  activate(nodes) %>% 
  as_tibble()
## # A tibble: 20 x 2

Edges can be manipulated likewise. I will just add a (meaningless, because we are dealing with a toy example) weight column.

toy_example_node_edge_attr <- toy_example_node_attr %>% 
  activate(edges) %>% 
  mutate(weight = sample(1:5, length(E(.)), replace = TRUE))

Another way of doing this is using a modified version of the pipe (%E>% or %N>%):

toy_example_node_attr %E>% 
  mutate(weight = sample(1:5, length(E(.)), replace = TRUE)) %N>%
  mutate(type = "random type")

Another handy thing is that you can access the edges when nodes are activated (using .E()) and vice versa (using .N()). This is handy for conditional manipulations. I assume that the toy example contains romantic relationships. Therefore, I can classify the relationships using the data on their gender.

toy_example_sex_orientation <- toy_example_node_edge_attr %>% 
  activate(edges) %>% # because I add a column to the edgelist
  mutate(sexual_orientation = case_when(.N()$female[from] == .N()$female[to] ~ "homosexual",
                                        .N()$female[from] != .N()$female[to] ~ "heterosexual"))

Using dplyr syntax for wrangling

As shown earlier, mutate() works like a charm.

Besides, filter()ing out either edges or nodes will exclude them from the entire object hence, if I remove nodes, their connections will be removed from the edgelist as well.

toy_example_sex_orientation %>% 
  activate(nodes) %>% 
  filter(female == 1) %>%  
  activate(edges) %>% 
  as_tibble()
## # A tibble: 0 x 4
## #  with 4 variables: from <int>, to <int>, weight <int>,
## #   sexual_orientation <chr>

Merging

Besides, all the joins are supported as well. If you want to add edge data, they need to contain from and to columns which refer to valid nodes.

There are also bind_*() functions which are graph-specific: bind_nodes(), bind_edges(), and bind_graphs(). The latter does not allow you to create edges between the different graphs, they rather become singular components in the same graph. If you want to merge them as they share nodes graph_join() is the way to go. It works like a full join hence keeps the individual edges from both graphs. Node names need to be provided and will be used for joining.

graph_1 <- play_erdos_renyi(20, 0.2, directed = TRUE) %>% 
  mutate(name = 1:20) # after creating a new graph, nodes are active by default
graph_2 <- play_erdos_renyi(50, 0.1, directed = TRUE) %>% 
  mutate(name = 1:50)

plot(graph_join(graph_1, graph_2))
## Joining, by = "name"

plot(bind_graphs(graph_1, graph_2))

reroute()

This function changes beginning and end nodes of edges. It has an subset = argument as well.

# reverse edges
graph_1 %E>%
  reroute(from = to, to = from)

morph() and unmorph()

Sometimes, you do not only want to make minor changes like the ones demonstrated in the former sections. This is where the morph() function comes in handy. It provides you with a couple of functions on how to split it. unmorph() returns to the entire graph plus the manipulations you have made.

Functions for morph()

Functions for morph(): https://tidygraph.data-imaginist.com/reference/morphers.html

So, lets check out some examples:

  • to_shortest-path()
from <- 4
to <- 3
play_erdos_renyi(50, 0.5) %N>%
  mutate(name = 1:50) %>% 
  morph(to_shortest_path, from = from, to = to, mode = "out")
## # A tbl_graph temporarily morphed to a shortest path representation
## # 
## # Original graph is a directed simple graph with 1 component
## # consisting of 50 nodes and 1291 edges
  • to_simple
edges <- tibble(
  from = c(1, 1:10),
  to = c(2, 1:10)
)
nodes <- tibble(
  name = 1:10
)

tbl_graph(nodes = nodes, edges = edges) %>% 
  morph(to_simple, remove_multiples = TRUE, remove_loops = TRUE) %>%
  activate(edges) %>% 
  mutate(indicator = 1) %>% 
  unmorph() 
## # A tbl_graph: 10 nodes and 11 edges
## #
## # A directed multigraph with 9 components
## #
## # Edge Data: 11 x 3 (active)
##    from    to indicator
##   <int> <int>     <dbl>
## 1     1     2         1
## 2     1     1        NA
## 3     2     2        NA
## 4     3     3        NA
## 5     4     4        NA
## 6     5     5        NA
## #  with 5 more rows
## #
## # Node Data: 10 x 1
##    name
##   <int>
## 1     1
## 2     2
## 3     3
## #  with 7 more rows

If you want to switch to your representation more permanently, use crystallize(). It will return a list containing the graph object(s) this is especially handy if you split it up into sub-groups (e.g., different components which are linked together)

edges <- tibble(
  from = c(1, 1:10),
  to = c(2, 1:10)
)
nodes <- tibble(
  name = 1:10
)

crystallize_example <- tbl_graph(nodes = nodes, edges = edges) %>% 
  morph(to_simple, remove_multiples = TRUE, remove_loops = TRUE) %>%
  activate(edges) %>% 
  mutate(indicator = 1) %>% 
  crystallize()

plot(crystallize_example$graph[[1]])

Sometimes you know that your crystallize() call will only return one object like in my example above. In this case, you can also use convert() as an abbreviation for both morph() and crystallize().

convert_example <- tbl_graph(nodes = nodes, edges = edges) %>% 
  convert(to_simple, remove_multiples = TRUE, remove_loops = TRUE)

plot(convert_example)
